874
00:34:51,345 --> 00:34:54,588
we tried to take space out of the middle, it disrupted a lot of things.

875
00:34:55,008 --> 00:34:59,151
It made the shape not feel like Manhattan and it disrupted the position of all of our

876
00:34:59,191 --> 00:34:59,591
landmarks.

877
00:35:00,696 --> 00:35:03,197
And so considering our goals of trying

878
00:35:03,217 --> 00:35:04,577
to make this feel like a real space,

879
00:35:05,098 --> 00:35:08,479
we knew that we would be OK if we took space out of the sides,

880
00:35:08,859 --> 00:35:10,700
but we needed to leave the space in the middle alone.

881
00:35:15,201 --> 00:35:19,423
And I think that all of the experimentation, all

882
00:35:19,443 --> 00:35:21,944
of the confirming that we did, and all the planning that we

883
00:35:21,984 --> 00:35:23,064
did, and all the research we did,

884
00:35:23,424 --> 00:35:25,985
really shows off when you compare the initial sketch

885
00:35:26,005 --> 00:35:26,705
to the final product.

886
00:35:26,725 --> 00:35:28,446
Because there are a lot of similarities between the two.

887
00:35:33,237 --> 00:35:35,878
And so reflecting on the actual process itself,

888
00:35:37,639 --> 00:35:40,160
during applying the process on Spider-Man,

889
00:35:40,420 --> 00:35:43,002
is when I really thought about experimenting with intent.

890
00:35:43,262 --> 00:35:45,663
And so thinking about this as a scientific process

891
00:35:45,703 --> 00:35:49,444
and not just as freeform experimentation,

892
00:35:49,464 --> 00:35:51,906
but trying to actually answer questions.

893
00:35:52,366 --> 00:35:55,187
And then also thinking about using evidence

894
00:35:55,227 --> 00:35:56,408
to support what I was trying to do.

895
00:35:57,307 --> 00:35:59,388
So again, one of the scary things about building Manhattan

896
00:35:59,769 --> 00:36:00,709
was it's a huge level.

897
00:36:01,189 --> 00:36:04,771
And we didn't have the time to try it once and then restart

898
00:36:04,851 --> 00:36:05,672
over and try it again.

899
00:36:06,172 --> 00:36:08,033
So we had to be sure and confident with everything

900
00:36:08,073 --> 00:36:08,773
we were trying to do.

901
00:36:09,274 --> 00:36:11,535
And we basically needed to accurately predict

902
00:36:11,815 --> 00:36:12,876
what the outcome was going to be.

903
00:36:13,416 --> 00:36:15,017
And I find that when you're trying

904
00:36:15,037 --> 00:36:17,638
to make accurate predictions, it's good to have evidence.

905
00:36:17,778 --> 00:36:20,219
So I started thinking about the experiments I did

906
00:36:20,760 --> 00:36:22,321
and the research I was doing as evidence

907
00:36:22,341 --> 00:36:24,902
when I was trying to predict how well the final level was

908
00:36:24,942 --> 00:36:25,422
going to come out.

909
00:36:27,750 --> 00:36:30,451
So in summary, you want to define,

910
00:36:30,832 --> 00:36:33,053
so define your thematic and your gameplay goals,

911
00:36:34,013 --> 00:36:35,534
form goals around key questions,

912
00:36:36,335 --> 00:36:37,716
and resolve conflicts you may have

913
00:36:37,756 --> 00:36:39,517
between gameplay and thematic goals.

914
00:36:40,877 --> 00:36:41,738
You want to do research,

915
00:36:42,238 --> 00:36:43,459
you want to make sure you do research

916
00:36:43,539 --> 00:36:45,300
even if you think you're familiar with the content,

917
00:36:45,640 --> 00:36:47,861
and you want to try to go beyond reference images.

918
00:36:48,522 --> 00:36:49,923
And be sure you play the games

919
00:36:50,403 --> 00:36:52,584
and make sure that you give the games the time they need

920
00:36:52,984 --> 00:36:54,465
to really understand the full experience.

921
00:36:56,239 --> 00:36:58,620
And then when you experiment, try to answer key questions.

922
00:36:58,720 --> 00:37:00,821
Try to build controlled experiments.

923
00:37:01,661 --> 00:37:03,382
Think of this phase like sketching,

924
00:37:03,482 --> 00:37:05,322
so don't get too hung up on details yet.

925
00:37:05,942 --> 00:37:07,423
And be OK with throwing things away.

926
00:37:07,483 --> 00:37:09,043
Being OK with starting over if you need to.

927
00:37:10,144 --> 00:37:12,685
And then confirming, you need to make sure you step back

928
00:37:12,745 --> 00:37:14,085
and verify your goals.

929
00:37:15,406 --> 00:37:17,246
Check your scale, your logic, your flow.

930
00:37:18,327 --> 00:37:21,588
And if you can, only move past this step with confidence.

931
00:37:22,891 --> 00:37:25,793
And then execute, this is where you define the final rough,

932
00:37:25,813 --> 00:37:27,034
this is where you lock down metrics,

933
00:37:27,554 --> 00:37:28,555
you clean up your edges.

934
00:37:30,236 --> 00:37:32,177
And everything should start to finally play

935
00:37:32,217 --> 00:37:33,138
like you expect it to.

936
00:37:34,059 --> 00:37:35,119
And then finally, reflect.

937
00:37:36,020 --> 00:37:37,121
Consider what you could have done better,

938
00:37:37,561 --> 00:37:40,703
consider what about how you can improve the process,

939
00:37:40,723 --> 00:37:42,084
and consider whether it's really too late

940
00:37:42,124 --> 00:37:43,665
to try to improve your level.

941
00:37:45,446 --> 00:37:45,706
And so.

942
00:37:46,648 --> 00:37:49,409
The main point I have is a base in Sunset Overdrive

943
00:37:49,769 --> 00:37:53,031
is a very different type of space from the city of Manhattan.

944
00:37:53,691 --> 00:37:57,253
Yet the same fundamental process was used to build both.

945
00:37:57,813 --> 00:38:00,314
And that's really the power of a good process.

