00:42:05,901 --> 00:42:07,182
of gameplay specifics like that?

1043
00:42:08,547 --> 00:42:10,988
I mean, we were trying to map that out from the beginning.

1044
00:42:11,488 --> 00:42:14,309
We tried to make sure that each of the locations...

1045
00:42:14,629 --> 00:42:16,150
I think one thing that helped that we knew

1046
00:42:16,230 --> 00:42:17,510
that a lot of those things were probably

1047
00:42:17,530 --> 00:42:18,951
gonna pivot around landmarks too,

1048
00:42:19,351 --> 00:42:21,111
because that makes for interesting gameplay

1049
00:42:21,151 --> 00:42:22,852
if you have a mission or something that takes place

1050
00:42:22,972 --> 00:42:24,693
at a well-known location, right?

1051
00:42:24,753 --> 00:42:25,893
Particularly in something like Manhattan.

1052
00:42:26,413 --> 00:42:28,434
So, we tried to make sure that there was

1053
00:42:28,974 --> 00:42:30,754
a good distribution of landmarks

1054
00:42:30,874 --> 00:42:33,915
to help people build missions around there.

1055
00:42:35,912 --> 00:42:37,173
We would map things out early.

1056
00:42:37,313 --> 00:42:38,514
So we would map things out early.

1057
00:42:38,554 --> 00:42:42,236
We would do sort of speculative mission flows

1058
00:42:42,276 --> 00:42:43,757
throughout the city, and then just

1059
00:42:43,777 --> 00:42:45,378
try to accommodate whenever missions did come up.

1060
00:42:46,159 --> 00:42:46,339
Thanks.

1061
00:42:49,140 --> 00:42:50,421
OK.

1062
00:42:50,561 --> 00:42:52,362
You mentioned playing games and studying them

1063
00:42:52,843 --> 00:42:55,985
to learn things from them and play through the whole thing

1064
00:42:56,005 --> 00:42:57,045
to learn things.

1065
00:42:57,065 --> 00:42:59,407
Do you have a specific process or things that you look for

1066
00:42:59,607 --> 00:43:02,649
or how you go about doing that to learn the most

1067
00:43:03,489 --> 00:43:05,330
and get the most out of it as a designer?

1068
00:43:05,963 --> 00:43:07,884
Yeah, I mean, obviously, it's a little bit easier

1069
00:43:07,904 --> 00:43:09,264
when you're making something like Spider-Man, right?

1070
00:43:09,284 --> 00:43:10,725
Because you just go play all the Spider-Man games.

1071
00:43:11,965 --> 00:43:14,086
But I also looked for, I try to find common elements

1072
00:43:14,126 --> 00:43:18,047
or common threads, or things that I want to achieve

1073
00:43:18,087 --> 00:43:21,088
that either have been done well, or maybe were tried

1074
00:43:21,108 --> 00:43:22,549
in kind of a crazy way in a different game.

1075
00:43:22,629 --> 00:43:25,850
So, obviously, you play through all the Spider-Man games,

1076
00:43:25,870 --> 00:43:28,631
but then there are other games that take place in New York,

1077
00:43:28,871 --> 00:43:31,372
and so it's important to try to play those games.

1078
00:43:33,084 --> 00:43:36,346
There are also games that are trying to go for just the feeling of New York.

1079
00:43:36,826 --> 00:43:42,328
And so I work with looking at games that achieve critical claim,

1080
00:43:42,568 --> 00:43:45,630
right, or are related to what I'm trying to do,

1081
00:43:46,510 --> 00:43:48,151
or to just do something unique and novel.

1082
00:43:48,291 --> 00:43:50,392
And in terms of finding those games, I guess

1083
00:43:50,412 --> 00:43:51,933
that could be a difficult challenge, right?

1084
00:43:51,953 --> 00:43:53,914
There's lots of diamonds in the rough out there.

1085
00:43:55,704 --> 00:43:57,666
I feel like that's why it's important just as much as you

1086
00:43:57,686 --> 00:43:59,508
